 138, 124, 134, 158, 151, 136, 133, 121, 117\n|y1Title=New deaths per day\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak data/Iran medical cases}}\n\n==See also==\n*[[2019\u20132020 coronavirus pandemic by country and territory]]\n*[[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic in Asia]]\n\n{{Portal bar|COVID-19|Iran|Medicine|Viruses}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons|Category:COVID-19 pandemic in Iran}}\n* Data and maps, frequently updated:\n** {{cite web |url=https://coronavirus-global.com/iran |title=Coronavirus Iran updates and news |trans-title=Latest news and statistics of coronavirus in Iran. |access-date=4 April 2020 |language=English, French, Spanish, Portuguese, German, Italian, Swedish, Norwegian, Finnish, Estonian, Russian}}\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n{{Iran topics}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Iran| ]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in Iran]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Iran]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in Asia|Iran]]\n", "name_user": "Dede2008", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAfter Nowruz (4 April - Up to now)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Iran"}
{"title_page": "Knud Rasmussen-class patrol vessel", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=P570 Knud Rasmussen.jpg\n|Ship caption=HDMS ''Knud Rasmussen''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=''Knud Rasmussen'' class\n|Builders=*Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n*Hull is built at the Polish Stocznia P\u00f3lnocna (Northern Shipyard) in Gdansk\n|Operators={{navy|Denmark}}\n|Class before={{sclass-|Agdlek|cutter|4}}\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=\n|Cost=\n|Built range=\n|In service range=\n|In commission range=2008\u2013present\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=3\n|Total ships completed=3\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=3\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship type=[[Patrol boat|Ocean patrol craft]] \n|Ship displacement=1,720 tons (2,050 t full load)\n|Ship length=*LOA {{convert|71.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n*LWL {{convert|61.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam={{convert|14.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship draft={{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship propulsion=2 x [[MAN B&W Diesel]] ALPHA 8L27/38 generating {{convert|2720|kW|HP|abbr=on}} each through RENK reduction gear \"Twin in/single out\"\n|Ship speed= {{convert|17|kn}}                     \n|Ship range={{convert|3000|nmi}}\n|Ship boats=1 x [[Storebro SB90E|SB90E]] for [[search and rescue]], 1x {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[RHIB]], 1 x {{convert|4.8|m|ft}} RHIB\n|Ship complement=18 + aircrew and transients (Accommodation for up to 43 in total) \n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[Terma A/S|Terma]] Scanter 4100 surface and air search radar\n*3 \u00d7 Furuno navigation radars\n*[[Saab AB|SAAB]] CEROS 200 radar and optronic tracking system and CWI illumination radar\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 [[Oto Melara 76 mm|76 mm gun Mk M/85 LvSa]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[Browning M2|12.7 mm heavy machine gun M/01 LvSa]]\n*[[RIM-162 ESSM|RIM-162 Evolved Sea Sparrow]] surface-to-air missiles (not fitted with)\n*[[MU90 Impact]] ASW-torpedo\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=Aft helicopter deck\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''''Knud Rasmussen'' class''' is a [[Ship class|class]] of [[Patrol boat|offshore patrol vessels]] operating in the [[Royal Danish Navy]] from 2008.<ref name=Rdn2008-02-19>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/navynews/2008/0220_KnudRasmussen.htm |title=Knud Rasmussen commissioned: First new Arctic Offshore Patrol Vessel Commissioned |date=18 February 2008 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Fnavynews%2F2008%2F0220_KnudRasmussen.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Rdn2007-11-19>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/theships/classes/knudrasmussen_class%282007%29.htm |title=Knud Rasmussen Class (2008-) |date=19 November 2007 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Ftheships%2Fclasses%2Fknudrasmussen_class%25282007%2529.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Rdn2007-11-17>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/navynews/2007/1009_SecondOPVarrived.htm |title=Second OPV in Skagen: Both new Off Shore Patrol Vessels together for the first time |date=19 November 2007 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Fnavynews%2F2007%2F1009_SecondOPVarrived.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Casr2008-05Knud>{{cite news |url=http://www.casr.ca/id-danish-naval-projects-rasmussen.htm |title=An Overview of Current, On-Going Danish Naval projects  2005-2009 Knud Rasmussen class Ice-Resistant OPV (Offshore Patrol Vessel) |date=May 2008 |author= |publisher=[[Canadian American Strategic Review]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.casr.ca%2Fid-danish-naval-projects-rasmussen.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009 |accessdate=2 August 2009}}</ref> Built to replace the {{sclass-|Agdlek|cutter|1}}s on a one-by-one basis, the ''Knud Rasmussen''-class vessels are significantly larger, enabling patrols further offshore.\n\nThe ships' normal tasks include fisheries inspections, environment protection, search and rescue, sovereignty enforcement, [[icebreaker]] assignments ([[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] 1A Super/[[Polar Class 6]]),<ref>{{cite journal | title = Implications of ice class for an offshore patrol vessel | first1 = RC | last1 = Braithwaite | first2 = D | last2 = Khan | year = 2014  | journal = Journal of Marine Engineering & Technology | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 17\u201327 | doi = 10.1080/20464177.2014.11658118 }}</ref> towage and salvage operations and general assistance to the Danish and Greenland governments (including police tasks). The class has a helicopter deck aft behind the superstructure but lacks an aircraft hangar. However, it can perform [[Rotors running refueling]] and can thus increase the endurance and the range of the helicopter. December 2013 a third ship of the class (HDMS ''Lauge Koch'') was ordered by the Danish Parliament. Service entry of the third ship will be 2016, with an estimated cost of 513 mill Dkr (US$ {{Format price|{{To USD|513000000|DNK}} }}).\n\n==Armament==\nThe standard armament consists of two {{convert|12.7|mm|in|adj=on|1}} heavy machine guns. This is supplemented by the two [[Stanflex]] modular mission payload slots (one on the foredeck, the other aft of the superstructure), which can be fitted with a multi-purpose gun, [[surface-to-air missile]]s, or [[anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] torpedoes, along with other non-weapon payloads. Another two container positions are \"prepared for\" but not installed on the starboard and port sides of the heli deck.\n\n==List of ships==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n![[Pennant number|Pennant<br>number]]\n!Name\n!Int'l [[Callsign|c/s]]\n![[Shipyard]]\n!Laid down\n!Launched\n!In service\n!Christened by\n!Decommissioned\n|-\n| P570\n| {{HDMS|Knud Rasmussen|P570|2}}\n| OVFG\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2005-11-21\n| 2006-10-19\n| 2008-02-18\n| J\u00f3annes ejdesgaard\n\n| -\n|-\n| P571\n| {{HDMS|Ejnar Mikkelsen|P571|2}}\n| OVFH\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2006-11-10\n| 2007-06-01\n| 2009-01-16\n| -\n| -\n|-\n| P572\n| {{HDMS|Lauge Koch|P572|2}}\n| OVFI\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2014-05\n| \n| 2017-12-11\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://forsvaret.dk/sitecollectiondocuments/smk/projekter/if/pr%C3%A6sentation_af_skib_-_if_-_endelig_version.pdf Official presentation (Danish)]\n\n{{Knud Rasmussen class patrol vessel}}\n\n[[Category:Patrol ship classes]]\n[[Category:Knud Rasmussen-class patrol vessels| ]]\n[[Category:Active patrol vessels of Denmark| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=P570 Knud Rasmussen.jpg\n|Ship caption=HDMS ''Knud Rasmussen''\n}}\n{{Infobox ship class overview\n|Name=''Knud Rasmussen'' class\n|Builders=*Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n*Hull is built at the Polish Stocznia P\u00f3lnocna (Northern Shipyard) in Gdansk\n|Operators={{navy|Denmark}}\n|Class before={{sclass-|Agdlek|cutter|4}}\n|Class after=\n|Subclasses=\n|Cost=\n|Built range=\n|In service range=\n|In commission range=2008\u2013present\n|Total ships building=\n|Total ships planned=3\n|Total ships completed=3\n|Total ships cancelled=\n|Total ships active=3\n|Total ships laid up=\n|Total ships lost=\n|Total ships retired=\n|Total ships preserved=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Ship type=[[Patrol boat|Ocean patrol craft]] \n|Ship displacement=1,720 tons (2,050 t full load)\n|Ship length=*LOA {{convert|71.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n*LWL {{convert|61.0|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship beam={{convert|14.6|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship draft={{convert|4.9|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n|Ship propulsion=2 x [[MAN B&W Diesel]] ALPHA 8L27/38 generating {{convert|2720|kW|HP|abbr=on}} each through RENK reduction gear \"Twin in/single out\"\n|Ship speed= {{convert|17|kn|km/h|abbr=on}}                     \n|Ship range={{convert|3000|nmi|km}}\n|Ship boats=1 x [[Storebro SB90E|SB90E]] for [[search and rescue]], 1x {{convert|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} [[RHIB]], 1 x {{convert|4.8|m|ft}} RHIB\n|Ship complement=18 + aircrew and transients (Accommodation for up to 43 in total) \n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[Terma A/S|Terma]] Scanter 4100 surface and air search radar\n*3 \u00d7 Furuno navigation radars\n*[[Saab AB|SAAB]] CEROS 200 radar and optronic tracking system and CWI illumination radar\n|Ship EW=\n|Ship armament=*1 \u00d7 [[Oto Melara 76 mm|76 mm gun Mk M/85 LvSa]]\n*2 \u00d7 [[Browning M2|12.7 mm heavy machine gun M/01 LvSa]]\n*[[RIM-162 ESSM|RIM-162 Evolved Sea Sparrow]] surface-to-air missiles (not fitted with)\n*[[MU90 Impact]] ASW-torpedo\n|Ship aircraft=\n|Ship aircraft facilities=Aft helicopter deck\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\nThe '''''Knud Rasmussen'' class''' is a [[Ship class|class]] of [[Patrol boat|offshore patrol vessels]] operating in the [[Royal Danish Navy]] from 2008.<ref name=Rdn2008-02-19>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/navynews/2008/0220_KnudRasmussen.htm |title=Knud Rasmussen commissioned: First new Arctic Offshore Patrol Vessel Commissioned |date=18 February 2008 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Fnavynews%2F2008%2F0220_KnudRasmussen.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Rdn2007-11-19>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/theships/classes/knudrasmussen_class%282007%29.htm |title=Knud Rasmussen Class (2008-) |date=19 November 2007 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Ftheships%2Fclasses%2Fknudrasmussen_class%25282007%2529.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Rdn2007-11-17>{{cite news |url=http://www.navalhistory.dk/english/navynews/2007/1009_SecondOPVarrived.htm |title=Second OPV in Skagen: Both new Off Shore Patrol Vessels together for the first time |date=19 November 2007 |author= |publisher=[[Royal Danish Navy]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.navalhistory.dk%2Fenglish%2Fnavynews%2F2007%2F1009_SecondOPVarrived.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009}}</ref><ref name=Casr2008-05Knud>{{cite news |url=http://www.casr.ca/id-danish-naval-projects-rasmussen.htm |title=An Overview of Current, On-Going Danish Naval projects  2005-2009 Knud Rasmussen class Ice-Resistant OPV (Offshore Patrol Vessel) |date=May 2008 |author= |publisher=[[Canadian American Strategic Review]] |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/query?url=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.casr.ca%2Fid-danish-naval-projects-rasmussen.htm&date=2009-09-12 |archivedate=12 September 2009 |accessdate=2 August 2009}}</ref> Built to replace the {{sclass-|Agdlek|cutter|1}}s on a one-by-one basis, the ''Knud Rasmussen''-class vessels are significantly larger, enabling patrols further offshore.\n\nThe ships' normal tasks include fisheries inspections, environment protection, search and rescue, sovereignty enforcement, [[icebreaker]] assignments ([[Finnish-Swedish ice class]] 1A Super/[[Polar Class 6]]),<ref>{{cite journal | title = Implications of ice class for an offshore patrol vessel | first1 = RC | last1 = Braithwaite | first2 = D | last2 = Khan | year = 2014  | journal = Journal of Marine Engineering & Technology | volume = 13 | issue = 3 | pages = 17\u201327 | doi = 10.1080/20464177.2014.11658118 }}</ref> towage and salvage operations and general assistance to the Danish and Greenland governments (including police tasks). The class has a helicopter deck aft behind the superstructure but lacks an aircraft hangar. However, it can perform [[Rotors running refueling]] and can thus increase the endurance and the range of the helicopter. December 2013 a third ship of the class (HDMS ''Lauge Koch'') was ordered by the Danish Parliament. Service entry of the third ship will be 2016, with an estimated cost of 513 mill Dkr (US$ {{Format price|{{To USD|513000000|DNK}} }}).\n\n==Armament==\nThe standard armament consists of two {{convert|12.7|mm|in|adj=on|1}} heavy machine guns. This is supplemented by the two [[Stanflex]] modular mission payload slots (one on the foredeck, the other aft of the superstructure), which can be fitted with a multi-purpose gun, [[surface-to-air missile]]s, or [[anti-submarine warfare|ASW]] torpedoes, along with other non-weapon payloads. Another two container positions are \"prepared for\" but not installed on the starboard and port sides of the heli deck.\n\n==List of ships==\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n![[Pennant number|Pennant<br>number]]\n!Name\n!Int'l [[Callsign|c/s]]\n![[Shipyard]]\n!Laid down\n!Launched\n!In service\n!Christened by\n!Decommissioned\n|-\n| P570\n| {{HDMS|Knud Rasmussen|P570|2}}\n| OVFG\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2005-11-21\n| 2006-10-19\n| 2008-02-18\n| J\u00f3annes ejdesgaard\n\n| -\n|-\n| P571\n| {{HDMS|Ejnar Mikkelsen|P571|2}}\n| OVFH\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2006-11-10\n| 2007-06-01\n| 2009-01-16\n| -\n| -\n|-\n| P572\n| {{HDMS|Lauge Koch|P572|2}}\n| OVFI\n| Karstensens Skibsv\u00e6rft\n| 2014-05\n| \n| 2017-12-11\n| -\n| -\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://forsvaret.dk/sitecollectiondocuments/smk/projekter/if/pr%C3%A6sentation_af_skib_-_if_-_endelig_version.pdf Official presentation (Danish)]\n\n{{Knud Rasmussen class patrol vessel}}\n\n[[Category:Patrol ship classes]]\n[[Category:Knud Rasmussen-class patrol vessels| ]]\n[[Category:Active patrol vessels of Denmark| ]]\n", "name_user": "Tupsumato", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Knud_Rasmussen-class_patrol_vessel"}
{"title_page": "Running for Grace", "text_new": "{{short description|2018 Family Movie directed by David L. Cunningham}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Running for Grace\n| image = Running for Grace poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption =\n| director = [[David L. Cunningham]]\n| producer = \n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David L. Cunningham]]\n* Christian Parkes\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ryan Potter]]\n* [[Matt Dillon]]\n* [[Jim Caviezel]]\n* Olivia Ritchie\n}}\n| music = \n| cinematography = Akis Konstantakopoulos\n| editing = \n| production companies = Kona Snow Pictures\n| distributor = [[Blue Fox Entertainment]]\n| released = {{Film date|2018|07|20}}\n| runtime = 110 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = \n| gross = $89,988<ref>{{cite website |title=Box Office Mojo |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2119532/?ref_=bo_se_r_1}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Running for Grace''''' is a 2018 American romance film directed by [[David L. Cunningham]]. The film stars [[Ryan Potter]], [[Matt Dillon]], [[Jim Caviezel]], and Olivia Ritchie.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Leydon |first=Joe |date=17 August 2018 |title=Film Review: \u2018Running for Grace\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/running-for-grace-review-1202909526/ |magazine=Variety |location= |publisher= |access-date=8 December 2018 }} </ref> The film was released on August 17, 2018 in the United States. \n\nThe film was shot on location in Hawaii and at Kona-based Honua Studios.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kay |first1=Jeremy |title=Matt Dillon, Jim Caviezel star in 'Jo, The Medicine Runner' for Blue Fox |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/matt-dillon-jim-caviezel-star-in-jo-the-medicine-runner-for-blue-fox-/5126328.article |website=ScreenDaily |accessdate=6 December 2018 |date=7 February 2018}}</ref> It was originally known as ''Jo, the Medicine Runner''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pitts |first1=Elizabeth |title=On location: Hawaii Island the star of new film \u2018Running for Grace\u2019 |url=http://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2018/07/20/entertainment/on-location-hawaii-island-the-star-of-new-film-running-for-grace/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=West Hawaii Today |date=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is set in the [[Kona Coffee Belt]] of Hawaii during the 1920s. Japanese immigrant laborers and the white upperclass live in a rigidly classist society. Jo (played as a child by Cole Takiue), an orphan of mixed-race lineage (''[[h\u0101fu]]''), finds himself ostracized by both groups until Doc ([[Matt Dillon]]), a white (''[[haole]]'') doctor from the mainland, is hired as a physician for workers on the plantation owned by Mr. Danielson ([[Nick Boraine]]). Doc has Jo run medicine and translate for him on the island.\n\nTen years later, Jo (played by [[Ryan Potter]]) falls in love with the plantation owner's daughter, Grace (Olivia Ritchie). They interact a few times at the Danielson's home under the guise of treating her ankle injury. Mr. Danielson meets a new doctor, Dr. Reyes ([[Jim Caviezel]]), and invites him to tend to the white upperclass residents of the island, even as his company is going bankrupt. Throughout this time, Doc has been taking several secret trips to see a lawyer in [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]]  about formally adopting Jo, even though it was illegal at that time to adopt a [[hapa|mixed-race]] child. Jo at first is impressed by the new doctor and his car, a [[Ford Model T]], and asks him to take him on as an assistant. However, when they go to treat Mr. Danielson's accountant, who had poisoned himself as a suicide attempt, Jo realizes that the doctor is a charlatan. Dr. Reyes later expresses a romantic interest in Grace, and her father, seeing it as an opportunity to save his plantation and way of life, encourages the proposal.\n\nMr. Danielson sets out on a trip to Hilo to discuss his looming bankruptcy with the bank, intending to inform them that Grace is marrying into a wealthy family. Along the way, he accidentally falls into a ditch and hits his head. Doc and Jo are the first to reach him and, on inspection, Doc fears Mr. Danielson's head injury is severe. He tells Jo to find Dr. Reyes so that they can use his motorcar to transport him. At his home, Mr. Danielson and his mother ([[Juliet Mills]]) insist Dr. Reyes treat his injury and that Doc and Jo leave. Moments later, Grace comes crying out of the house announcing that her father is dead. Grace's grandmother and Dr. Reyes watch Grace and Jo embrace, and Grace's grandmother scolds Grace and pulls her away.\n\nThat night, Doc and Jo are walking back to their house. Along the way, Dr. Reyes purposefully chases them in his car and tries to run them over. Doc manages to push Jo out of the way, but gets hit himself and dies shortly afterward. Dr. Reyes threatens to kill Jo if he doesn't leave town. Later, Jo returns to his mother's house and is found by the Hilo lawyer who informs him that Doc's adoption was a success. Jo runs to the scheduled wedding between Dr. Reyes and Grace and asks for her hand in marriage. Grace's caretaker of several years, Miss Hanabusa (Rumi Oyama), approves the proposal and informs everyone that Mr. Danielson was bankrupt.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Ryan Potter]] as Jo\n* [[Matt Dillon]] as \"Doc\"\n* [[Jim Caviezel]] as Doctor Reyes\n* Olivia Ritchie as Grace Danielson\n* [[Nick Boraine]] as Mr. Danielson\n* Rumi Oyama as Miss Hanabusa\n* [[Juliet Mills]] as Grace's grandmother\n* [[Stelio Savante]] as Mayor<ref>{{cite news |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Stelio Savante talks 'Running for Grace,' technology, Viola Davis |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/stelio-savante-talks-running-for-grace-technology-viola-davis/article/531052 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=Digital Journal |date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Cole Takiue as young Jo\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released two weeks early in Hawaii before it received its mainland release in the United States on Aug 17, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title='Running for Grace' tells tale of segregated coffee fields on Hawaii island |url=https://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/wake-up-2day/-running-for-grace-tells-tale-of-segregated-coffee-fields-on-big-island/1313301548 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=khon2}}</ref> The film first premiered in three movie theaters in Hawaii on July 20, 2018.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title |tt5696326}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|running_for_grace}}\n* [https://www.runningforgracemovie.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s romance films]]\n[[Category:American romance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2018 Family Movie directed by David L. Cunningham}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name = Running for Grace\n| image = Running for Grace poster.jpg\n| alt = \n| caption =\n| director = [[David L. Cunningham]]\n| producer = \n| writer = {{Plainlist|\n* [[David L. Cunningham]]\n* Christian Parkes\n}}\n| starring = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Ryan Potter]]\n* [[Matt Dillon]]\n* [[Jim Caviezel]]\n* Olivia Ritchie\n}}\n| music = \n| cinematography = Akis Konstantakopoulos\n| editing = \n| production companies = Kona Snow Pictures\n| distributor = [[Blue Fox Entertainment]]\n| released = {{Film date|2018|07|20}}\n| runtime = 110 minutes\n| country = United States\n| language = English\n| budget = \n| gross = $89,988<ref>{{cite website |title=Box Office Mojo |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/title/tt2119532/?ref_=bo_se_r_1}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''Running for Grace''''' is a 2018 American romance film directed by [[David L. Cunningham]]. The film stars [[Ryan Potter]], [[Matt Dillon]], [[Jim Caviezel]], and Olivia Ritchie.<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Leydon |first=Joe |date=17 August 2018 |title=Film Review: \u2018Running for Grace\u2019 |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/reviews/running-for-grace-review-1202909526/ |magazine=Variety |location= |publisher= |access-date=8 December 2018 }} </ref> The film was released on August 17, 2018 in the United States. \n\nThe film was shot on location in Hawaii and at Kona-based Honua Studios.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Kay |first1=Jeremy |title=Matt Dillon, Jim Caviezel star in 'Jo, The Medicine Runner' for Blue Fox |url=https://www.screendaily.com/news/matt-dillon-jim-caviezel-star-in-jo-the-medicine-runner-for-blue-fox-/5126328.article |website=ScreenDaily |accessdate=6 December 2018 |date=7 February 2018}}</ref> It was originally known as ''Jo, the Medicine Runner''.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pitts |first1=Elizabeth |title=On location: Hawaii Island the star of new film \u2018Running for Grace\u2019 |url=http://www.westhawaiitoday.com/2018/07/20/entertainment/on-location-hawaii-island-the-star-of-new-film-running-for-grace/ |accessdate=8 December 2018 |agency=West Hawaii Today |date=20 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nThe film is set in the [[Kona Coffee Belt]] of Hawaii during the 1920s. Japanese immigrant laborers and the white upperclass live in a rigidly classist society. Jo (played as a child by Cole Takiue), an orphan of mixed-race lineage (''[[h\u0101fu]]''), finds himself ostracized by both groups until Doc ([[Matt Dillon]]), a white (''[[haole]]'') doctor from the mainland, is hired as a physician for workers on the plantation owned by Mr. Danielson ([[Nick Boraine]]). Doc has Jo run medicine and translate for him on the island.\n\nTen years later, Jo (played by [[Ryan Potter]]) falls in love with the plantation owner's daughter, Grace (Olivia Ritchie). They interact a few times at the Danielson's home under the guise of treating her ankle injury. Mr. Danielson meets a new doctor, Dr. Reyes ([[Jim Caviezel]]), and invites him to tend to the white upperclass residents of the island, even as his company is going bankrupt. Throughout this time, Doc has been taking several secret trips to see a lawyer in [[Hilo, Hawaii|Hilo]]  about formally adopting Jo, even though it was illegal at that time to adopt a [[hapa|mixed-race]] child. Jo at first is impressed by the new doctor and his car, a [[Ford Model T]], and asks him to take him on as an assistant. However, when they go to treat Mr. Danielson's accountant, who had poisoned himself as a suicide attempt, Jo realizes that the doctor is a charlatan. Dr. Reyes later expresses a romantic interest in Grace, and her father, seeing it as an opportunity to save his plantation and way of life, encourages the proposal.\n\nMr. Danielson sets out on a trip to Hilo to discuss his looming bankruptcy with the bank, intending to inform them that Grace is marrying into a wealthy family. Along the way, he accidentally falls into a ditch and hits his head. Doc and Jo are the first to reach him and, on inspection, Doc fears Mr. Danielson's head injury is severe. He tells Jo to find Dr. Reyes so that they can use his motorcar to transport him. At his home, Mr. Danielson and his mother ([[Juliet Mills]]) insist Dr. Reyes treat his injury and that Doc and Jo leave. Moments later, Grace comes crying out of the house announcing that her father is dead. Grace's grandmother and Dr. Reyes watch Grace and Jo embrace, and Grace's grandmother scolds Grace and pulls her away.\n\nThat night, Doc and Jo are walking back to their house. Along the way, Dr. Reyes purposefully chases them in his car and tries to run them over. Doc manages to push Jo out of the way, but gets hit himself and dies shortly afterward. Dr. Reyes threatens to kill Jo if he doesn't leave town. Later, Jo returns to his mother's house and is found by the Hilo lawyer who informs him that Doc's adoption was a success. Jo runs to the scheduled wedding between Dr. Reyes and Grace and asks for her hand in marriage. Grace's caretaker of several years, Miss Hanabusa (Rumi Oyama), approves the proposal and informs everyone that Mr. Danielson was bankrupt.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Ryan Potter]] as Jo\n* [[Matt Dillon]] as \"Doc\"\n* [[Jim Caviezel]] as Doctor Reyes\n* Olivia Ritchie as Grace Danielson\n* [[Nick Boraine]] as Mr. Danielson\n* Rumi Oyama as Miss Hanabusa\n* [[Juliet Mills]] as Grace's grandmother\n* [[Stelio Savante]] as Mayor<ref>{{cite news |last1=Papadatos |first1=Markos |title=Stelio Savante talks 'Running for Grace,' technology, Viola Davis |url=http://www.digitaljournal.com/entertainment/entertainment/stelio-savante-talks-running-for-grace-technology-viola-davis/article/531052 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=Digital Journal |date=3 September 2018}}</ref>\n* Cole Takiue as young Jo\n\n==Release==\nThe film was released two weeks early in Hawaii before it received its mainland release in the United States on Aug 17, 2018.<ref>{{cite news |title='Running for Grace' tells tale of segregated coffee fields on Hawaii island |url=https://www.khon2.com/news/local-news/wake-up-2day/-running-for-grace-tells-tale-of-segregated-coffee-fields-on-big-island/1313301548 |accessdate=12 December 2018 |work=khon2}}</ref> The film first premiered in three movie theaters in Hawaii on July 20, 2018.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title |tt5696326}}\n* [https://www.runningforgracemovie.com/ Official website]\n\n[[Category:2018 films]]\n[[Category:2010s romance films]]\n[[Category:American romance films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n", "name_user": "LudaChrisKlein", "label": "safe", "comment": "add Rotten Tomatoes link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Running_for_Grace"}
